   <note>Encloses a printed circular which suggests that Eaton made a dishonest arrangement with the A.S. Barnes Co., whereby he agreed to recommend their textbooks in return for a $3000 loan for his bankrupt brother. Accuses Eaton of going beyond his legal rights as Superintendent of Public Instruction and forcing a particular line of books upon the schools. Launches into heated criticism of the circular`s authors, pointing out that the publishers of inferior, pro-Southern textbooks are probably behind it.</note>
